# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-rules-football-in-catalonia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/2005-eu-cup-australian-rules-football] The **2005 EU Cup** of Australian rules football was held in London (England) on 9 October 2005, with 10 national teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/2005-eu-cup-australian-rules-football] The tournament was won by Belgium who were crowned European Champions after defeating Sweden in the final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/2008-eu-cup-australian-rules-football] The **2008 EU Cup** of Australian rules football was held in Prague (Czech Republic) on 11 October 2008, with 12 teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/2008-eu-cup-australian-rules-football] The championship was won by England, defeating Croatia in the final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/49th-parallel-cup] The **49th Parallel Cup** (formerly PanAm Cup) is an annual representative Australian rules football match between the United States and Canada first contested in 1999.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/49th-parallel-cup] Since 2007 the women's teams have also contested the cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/49th-parallel-cup] The men's matches are contested between the United States men's team ("The Revolution") and Canada's men's team ("The Northwind") while the women's matches are contested between the United States women's team ("The Freedom") and Canada's women's team ("The Northern Lights").
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/49th-parallel-cup] The cup is historically paused during the Australian Football International Cup year to enable the countries to compete at that tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/49th-parallel-cup] Between 2015 and 2021 the cup went into recess for several reasons, primarily due to the 2017 Australian Football International Cup followed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] The **AFL Asia Cup** is a triennial international tournament in Australian rules football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] It is the biggest international tournament in the sport that is open to all nations in Asia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] It was created as a replacement of the AFL International Cup alongside the AFL Transatlantic Cup and the AFL Pacific Cup after the competition was affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] In August 2021, the AFL announced that the IC would return in 2023 to align with its original three-year schedule but did not announce the host.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] On 22 April 2022, the AFL announced it was postponing the International Cup until 2024 citing "significant investment required from the AFL to host the event".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] However, on 24 July 2023, the AFL announced that, in lieu of the International Cup, that it would be sponsoring three regional events in 2024: the Trans-Atlantic Cup, the Asia Cup, and the Pacific Cup to be hosted by an international affiliate.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] The AFL gave no indication as to when the International Cup would be resumed, however indicated that these are the only AFL sanctioned international tournaments since 2017 (effectively nullifying the 2019 and 2022 AFL Europe Championship).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] AFL Canada was announced as host of the Transatlantic Cup to be held at the Humber College Oval at Colonel Samuel Smith Park in Toronto on August 2–11, The Maroochydore Multi Sports Complex on the Sunshine Coast, Queensland was announced as the host of the Pacific Cup on 14–24 November.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] Thanh Long Sports Center in Vietnam would host the Asia Cup at in Ho Chi Minh City from December 6–8 in 2024.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] The AFL announced strict selection criteria, that each player must hold citizenship for the country that they are representing and must have played in from a local competition in that country.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-asia-cup] The 2024 competition was contested by 10 teams in the men's division and 4 teams in the women's division.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe-championship] The **AFL Europe Championship** is a triennial international Australian football competition played between European national teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe-championship] The European Championship is played in a full traditional 18-a-side format (formerly 16-a-side) unlike the Euro Cup which has a 9-a-side format.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe-championship] It is organised by AFL Europe and held every three years.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe-championship] Eligibility is similar to the Australian Football International Cup with national team representatives restricted to nationals - citizens who were resident in the country between the ages of 10 and 16.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe-championship] The inaugural competition was played in Sweden and Denmark in August 2010.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe-championship] The 2013 championships were held in Ireland in August 2013.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe-championship] A women's division was added in 2016 which was won by host nation Great Britain.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe-championship] Historically the competition has been dominated by Great Britain and Ireland who between them have won every edition of the competition, both men's and women's, up to the 2022 tournament, while Germany and the Scandinavian teams have also featured regularly in the final phases.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] AFL Europe also organises the European combine which provides a direct pathway to the Australian Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] Australian football has been played regularly in Europe since the late 1980s when leagues formed in England and Denmark.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] These first leagues led to the first international game between two European teams was played in 1994 between Great Britain and Denmark.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] As more leagues were formed, more international games began to be organised.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] Historical international competitions played by European teams include the Atlantic Alliance Cup, Central European Australian Football League Championships and the European Australian Football Tri-nations Tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The growth of Australian football in Europe led to the need for a central body that was accountable to the member organisations.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] At the 2005 EU Cup a conference was held which formed the body *Aussie Rules Europe* as a promotional body.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] *ARE* was superseded after a conference at the 2009 EU Cup the decision was made to form such a body at another conference the following January.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The January conference was held in Frankfurt, Germany and the *European Australian Football Association* was founded.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] At an October, 2010 conference in Parabiago, Italy the members of the *EAFA* voted to change the organisations's name to *AFL Europe*, to fall in line with the Australian Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] Beginning in 2013 the annual Colleges and Universities Cup is named after current AFL Chairman, Mike Fitzpatrick.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] Generally played by Irish and English Universities and Colleges, with the 2016 edition being held in Birmingham for the second year running.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] A new event first held in March 2015, contested as a one-day lightning carnival involving the club champions of all the various European leagues.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The inaugural Champions League was won by the West London Wildcats in Amsterdam.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] Beginning in 2012 and played in Villers-Bretonneux to commemorate the ANZAC's and the historic liberation of the town in World War I by Australian forces.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] A team of Australian players selected based on their connection to the ANZAC heritage to play in a game against the France national team, which is a centrepiece of the annual commemorations.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The current tally stands at 4 wins to Australia and 3 wins to France.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] Starting in 2015, the first corporate event held by AFL Europe to raise awareness of Aussie Rules internationally was held in Australia House in London.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The function was run in conjunction with the South Australia Club and was hosted by Bill Muirhead (Agent General for South Australia and AFL Europe Ambassador).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The ticketed event provided a unique opportunity for attendees to connect with the UK and Australian business communities while creating exposure for AFL Europe and our great game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] An annual nine-a-side footy competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The Euro Cup was originally known as the *EU Cup*, the name was changed after teams representing non European Union countries started participating.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The Euro Cup is partially intended as a developmental tool to allow participation for countries without enough players to form a full team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] Held every three years, this full format competition determines the Champions of Europe and has taken place twice since the inaugural championship in Denmark and Sweden in 2010.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The reigning champions are Ireland who won the most recent championship on home soil with a goal on the final siren against neighbours Great Britain, maintaining a 100% record in the Championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] AFL Europe also support a range of events and tournaments throughout the UK and Europe which can be seen in the Calendar on the AFL Europe Website.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The *Legion* represents the whole of Europe in Australian football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The Legion's first game was an Under 21 game against the AFL-AIS Academy Australian Under 17 team in London, England.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The Europe team had only been together for three days, which showed in the **27.21 (183)**-**2.0 (12)** scoreboard.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-europe] The Legion's colours are the blue and gold of the Flag of Europe and white.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-pacific-cup] The **AFL Pacific Cup** is a triennial international tournament in Australian rules football open to all nations in Oceania and Southern Africa.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-pacific-cup] It was created as a replacement of the AFL International Cup alongside the AFL Asia Cup and the AFL Transatlantic Cup after the competition was affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-pacific-cup] The 2024 AFL Pacific Cup was played at the Maroochydore Multisports Complex and contested in four divisions: Open Men, Open Women, Under 17 Boys & Under 17 Girls.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/afl-pacific-cup] It resulted in Papua New Guinea winning both the Open Men & Under 17 Girls championships and Nauru winning both the Open Women and Under 17 Boys championships.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/australian-rules-football-in-catalonia] There have been several teams playing the Catalan League: Belfry Valls, Cornellà Bocs, Barcelona Stars, Valls Fire, Wendells Salou, Coyotes Alt Camp, Gabas Tarragona, Lleida Coiots and Picamoixons Birds.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/australian-rules-football-in-catalonia] In 2009 the Catalan league was played by Belfry Valls, Cornellà Bocs, Andorra Crows and Perpignan Tigers.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/australian-rules-football-in-catalonia] The Catalonia national team has played three EU Cups in 2005, 2007, and 2008.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/australian-rules-football-in-catalonia] Catalonia was in the first EU Cup in 2005 in London, playing with teams representing Scotland, England, Germany, Sweden, Israel, Netherlands, France, Austria and Belgium.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/australian-rules-football-in-catalonia] Although other teams had expatriate Australians, all the Catalan players were from Catalonia, finishing in the seventh place.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/australian-rules-football-in-catalonia] The second EU Cup was held in Hamburg, with twelve teams representing Austria, Belgium, Catalonia, Czech Republic, England, Finland, France, Germany, Netherlands, Spain, Sweden and a team called EU Crusaders.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/australian-rules-football-in-catalonia] Again, Catalonia played with no expatriates, and this time got the eighth place.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/australian-rules-football-in-catalonia] The 2008 EU Cup was played in Prague, and Catalonia competed with England, Finland, Czech Republic, France, Germany, The Netherlands, Scotland, Croatia, Sweden, Austria and the EU Crusaders.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-catalonia/australian-rules-football-in-catalonia] At the end, Catalans reached the seventh place.
